==Reception==
===Critical reception===
''The American Girls Premiere'' was released to mostly positive reception, with praise being given for providing children a "creative outlet"; a number of reviewers however criticized the user interface to be intimidating and complicated.<ref name="Barnabel">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1999/01/03/education/software-toonsville-tutors.html|title=Software; Toonsville Tutors|last=Barnabel|first=Josh|date=January 3, 1999|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name="Rosenberg">{{cite news | last = Rosenberg | first = Ronald | title = Edutainment software abounds; quality varies | work = [[The Boston Globe]] | date = December 14, 1997 | accessdate = September 20, 2016 | url = https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8447169.html | publisher = via HighBeam {{Subscription required}} }}</ref> Children's software review site SuperKids noted that "Those who chose to spend time with the program were delighted with their creations,"<ref name="SKPremiere" /> Lisa Karen Savignano of [[AllGame]] also noted the game's steep learning curve and limited selection of scenarios and props for authoring stage productions, but gave ''American Girls Premiere'' a largely positive review, stating "I think any girl would be entertained by this and it may start them on the road to creating not just plays, but stories and art of their own,"<ref name="Savignano"/> Kevin Mukhar of [[Computer Shopper (US magazine)|Computer Shopper]] thought the game would provide hours of open-ended play to young girls ages 7–12 who liked the ''American Girl'' franchise.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-19994381.html|title=The American Girls Premiere|last=Mukhar|first=Kevin|date=December 1, 1997|work=Computer Shopper|access-date=|via=Highbeam}}</ref> A reviewer from The Wisconsin State Journal praised the game for being "historically accurate", easy to use, and providing players with "limitless creativity".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-69505194.html|title=DOLLED-UP CD A HIT|last=|first=|date=November 7, 1997|work=The Wisconsin State Journal|access-date=|via=Highbeam}}</ref> The Buffalo News commented that the title wouldn't appeal to the "easily bored" or "readily frustrated", but that it would thrill players who were willing to invest both the time and energy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-22960656.html|title=KNOW THE FACTS, THEN GO FOR THE PROGRAMMERS' BEST|last=GALARNEAU|first=ANDREW Z.|date=November 27, 1997|work=The Buffalo News|access-date=|via=Highbeam}}</ref> The Capital Times praised the artwork as "rich and detailed", and noted that the interface was user-friendly.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=September 26, 1997|title=AMERICAN GIRLS GET VIRTUAL DOLL HOUSE.(Today's Business)|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-69509305.html}}</ref> Playthings deemed it a "winner".<ref>{{Cite journal|date=January 1, 2000|title=Atlanta.(Brief Article)|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-59426855.html}}</ref> Clint Basinger of ''Lazy Game Reviews'' also criticized ''Premiere'''s similarity to ''Opening Night'' and what he saw as limited educational value, but praised its appeal to fans of the American Girl franchise, calling it a "neat little program" and a "fascinating industry case study" on [[Women and video games|video games aimed at girls]] and [[White-label product|repackaging]] an existing product to drive sales through the use of a licensed property.<ref name="Basinger">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KqGwUffHyCo|title=American Girls Premiere: Text-To-Speech Mayhem|last=Basinger|first=Clint|date=21 April 2017|work=Lazy Game Reviews|publisher=[[YouTube]]|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>

Many reviewers noted that ''The American Girls Premiere'' was a prime example of video games targeted at the female demographic. Deborah Porterfield of the [[Chicago Sun-Times]] described the title as "for girls" and "girl-oriented".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4405381.html|title=Guide to some new girl-oriented computer games|last=Porterfield|first=Deborah|date=September 23, 1997|work=Chicago Sun-Times|access-date=|via=Highbeam}}</ref> The Buffallo News suggested that the game was "at the top of many girls' Christmas wish lists".<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=COMPUTER GAME BRINGS AMERICAN GIRLS TO LIFE|last=LoTempio|first=Elizabeth|date=November 11, 1997|work=The Buffalo News|access-date=|via=Highbeam}}</ref> Citing this title as an example, The Boston Globe reviewer Joann Muller suggested that while the video game industry had begun to make commercially successful titles that appealed to the female demographic, the rushed targeting of games directly to girls could "perpetuate gender stereotypes" and "[not] teach girls anything of value about computers".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8458666.html|title=A GAME OF THEIR OWN NEW COMPUTER SOFTWARE AIMS TO ENTERTAIN AND EDUCATE PRE-TEENAGE GIRLS|last=Muller|first=Joann|date=March 30, 1998|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=|via=Highbeam}}</ref> The Buffalo News thought this game was the first "girl-targeted software" from The Learning Company, a company that had built its catalogue from "gender-neutral educational software".<ref name=":0" /> Rocky Mountain News reported that Children's Software Revue gave the title a "tentative endorsement" due to offering a "female spin" to traditional video game genres such as adventure.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=November 24, 1997|title=SOFTWARE BYTES.(Business)(SoftWARE page)(Review)|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-67745146.html}}</ref>

===Sales===
In December 1997, the game "achieved the highest monthly dollar and unit sales of any single product" in the history of The Learning Company up to that point.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://search.proquest.com.dbgw.lis.curtin.edu.au/docview/450040829?rfr_id=info%3Axri%2Fsid%3Aprimo|title=The American Girls Premiere Top Ranked Educational Title in December For Third Consecutive Month|last=|first=|date=January 23, 1998|work=PR Newswire|access-date=|via=Proquest}}</ref> In March 1998, The Boston Globe said the girls' category of the video game market was "exploding" with titles such as ''[[Barbie Fashion Designer]]'' (by [[Mattel]]), ''The American Girls Premiere, [[Let's Talk About Me]],'' (by [[Simon & Schuster|Simon & Schuster Interactive]]) and ''[[Rockett's New School]]'' (by [[Purple Moon]]).<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8460578.html|title=VIRTUAL EQUALITY? SOFTWARE FIRMS FIND NEW NICHE: GAMES FOR GIRLS|last=Muller|first=Joann|date=March 29, 1998|work=The Boston Globe|access-date=|via=Highbeam}}</ref> In July 1998, The Buffalo News reported that The Learning Company had captured 20.3% of the girl video game market with this video game.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=July 21, 1998|title=GAME MAKERS FINALLY REALIZE GIRLS PLAY, TOO|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-23058283.html}}</ref>

===Accolades===
The game was nominated at the 1998 [[Interactive Achievement Award]] for Computer Innovation,<ref name="Awards">{{cite web|url=http://www.interactive.org/awards/annual_awards.asp?idAward=1998 |title=AISA Annual Awards -> 1st Annual Awards |work=interactive.org |publisher=AISA |accessdate=June 15, 2009 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090203065916/http://interactive.org/awards/annual_awards.asp?idAward=1998 |archivedate=February 3, 2009 }}</ref> and won a Gold Award from the [[Parents' Choice Foundation]].<ref name="Oldenburg">{{cite web|url=http://www.parents-choice.org/product.cfm?product_id=607&StepNum=1&award=aw|title=The American Girls Premiere|last=Oldenburg|first=Don|work=[[Parents' Choice Foundation]]|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref> The game also won a Mom's Choice Software award for Fall 1997,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=19971122&id=hHIxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=7A0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3495,3179844|title=Toledo Blade – Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=September 20, 2016}}</ref> and a 1998 selection in [[American Library Association]]'s Great Interactive Software for Kids List.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ala.org/awardsgrants/awards/267/all_years|title=Great Interactive Software for Kids List  (HISTORICAL) {{!}} Awards & Grants|website=www.ala.org|access-date=September 20, 2016}}</ref>

==Legacy==
In a similar vein to ''[[Moonbase Alpha (video game)|Moonbase Alpha]]'', ''The American Girls Premiere'' has gained a [[cult video game|cult following]] due to its use of a [[text-to-speech]] system by [[Lernout & Hauspie]], which most players find to be ironically appealing. Adding to the unintentional humor is the lack of collision detection and other quirks within the game engine allowing characters to perform unusual movements, which led to a number of parody [[machinima]] clips on [[YouTube]] and other video sharing platforms.<ref name="vice">{{cite web|url=https://motherboard.vice.com/en_us/article/the-american-girls-pc-games-text-to-speech-feature-was-great-for-dick-jokes|title=The 'American Girls' PC Game's Text-To-Speech Feature Was Great for Dick Jokes - Motherboard|work=[[Vice (magazine)|Vice]]|accessdate=26 April 2017}}</ref>

